    <subsection xml:id="Question_3_1_3">
    <title> Problem 3</title>
    <ol marker="(a)">
        <li>
            <p>
                Any integer is of one of the following forms:
                <md>
                    <mrow> 6k+0 \amp = 3(3k)+0</mrow>
                    <mrow> 6k+1 \amp = 3(2k)+1</mrow>
                    <mrow> 6K+2 \amp = 3(2k)+2</mrow>
                    <mrow> 6k+3 \amp = 3(2k+1)+0</mrow>
                    <mrow> 6k+4 \amp = 3(2k+1)+1</mrow>
                    <mrow> 6k+5 \amp 3(2k+1)+2.</mrow>
                </md>

                So, if an integer is of the form <m>3n+1</m>, then it is either of the form <m>6k+1</m> or <m>6k+4</m>. An integer of the form <m>6k+4=2(3k+2)</m> is never prime so a prime of the form <m>3n+1</m> must also of the form <m>6m+1</m>.
                
                Any integer <m>k</m> can be written in the form <m>k=6k+r</m> where <m>r=0,1,2,3,4, \text{ or} 5</m>.
                Suppose <m>6m+1</m> is not prime
            </p>
        </li>

        <li>
            <p>
                All primes are of the form <m>3k+1</m> or <m>3k+2</m>.  Suppose an integer, <m>w</m>, is of the form <m>3n+2</m> and that all of its prime factors are of the form <m>3k+1</m>. That is:
                <md>
                    w=(3k_1+1)(3k_2+1)\cdots(3k_q+1).
                </md>
                
                Expand the right hand side to see that 
                <md>
                    2=3(\text{ some integer })+1
                </md>
                which contradicts <m>w</m> being of the form <m>3n+2</m>.  Thus <m>w</m> must have at least one prime factor of the form <m>3n+2</m>. 
                

            </p>
        </li>
    </ol>
    </subsection>
        
